  "text": "In the current research, we propose that odd-ending pricing is especially effective for hedonic consumption because it serves as justification for such purchases. Hedonic products are often thought of as more discretionary than utilitarian products [CITATION_1] . Thus, consumers feel a need to justify their decision to buy a hedonic product and feel guilty if they cannot. We argue that because odd-ending prices are perceived as price discounts, they can be used as justification for hedonic consumption, reducing anticipated guilt and increasing the likelihood of purchase.",
  "correct_citation": {
